                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     SPORT BRIEFS
                                                                    No renewal of Lawson contract  Karachi: The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) on Monday made it clear that it would not be renewing the contract of national team coach, Geoff Lawson when it expires next year.  PCB Chairman, Ejaz Butt in his first press conference in Lahore, said that he considered Lawson as a useless coach but could not sack him due to financial problems.  ldquo;We will suffer huge financial losses if we sack him. We have to pay him compensation of three months salary if we remove him now, rdquo; Butt said.
  ldquo;But one thing is clear he will no longer be the coach of the team when his two-year contract expires next year, rdquo; he added.  CCI unsure  Mumbai: The Cricket Club of India (CCI) has not yet been earmarked to host Champions T20 League ties in December at the Brabourne Stadium which is also the venue of the second and final Test between India and England in the same month.  IPL auction  Mumbai: The Indian Premier League (IPL) has increased its cap on the number of international players in a team and would conduct an auction next year to bring new players into the league, says Our Correspondent. The auction would be conducted on February 6.   Plews no more  Calcutta: The International Cricket Council (ICC) paid its tribute to former international umpire Nigel Plews, who died on Monday at the age of 74. Plews was suffering from kidney cancer, says A Staff Reporter.   CK Nayudu  Rajkot: Saurashtra on Monday secured three points in the Col CK Nayudu Trophy Under-22 cricket meet although their match against Mumbai ended in a draw.   Warriors win  Ahmedabad: Dhaka Warriors won their ICL Twenty20 Championship match beating Delhi Giants by 62 runs on Monday.  BRIEF SCORES
  Dhaka Warriors 174/5, Delhi Giants 112  NZ on top  Chittagong: Aaron Redmond hit an unbeaten half-century to put New Zealand in a promising position at the end of Day IV of the first Test against Bangladesh on Monday. 
